*{{Cite magazine|title=Transvaal Technical Institute|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AAkAAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA627|magazine=Page's Engineering Weekly|number=10|editor-last=Page|editor-first=David|last=|first=|date=1904|publisher=Page's Engineering Weekly|page=|pages=|doi=|isbn=|pmid=|location=|language=en|access-date=|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1949/04/29/archives/sir-fabian-ware-buried-war-dead-founder-of-imperial-graves.html|title=Sir Fabian Ware, Buried War Dead: Founder of Imperial Graves Commission Dies -- Guarded Plots in 2 World Conflicts|last=|first=|date=29 April 1949|work=New York Times|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724132235/https://www.nytimes.com/1949/04/29/archives/sir-fabian-ware-buried-war-dead-founder-of-imperial-graves.html|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live|ref={{harvid|New York Times|1949}}}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box\n| title = Editor of the ''[[Morning Post]]''\n| years = 1905\u20131911\n| before = [[Spenser Wilkinson]]\n| after = [[Howell Arthur Gwynne|Howell Gwynne]]\n}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Edmund Beale Sargant]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = Director of Education for the [[Transvaal Colony]]\n| years = 1903\u20131905\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = John Adamson<sup>1</sup>\n}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = '''Position created'''\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = Vice-Chairman,<br/>[[Imperial War Graves Commission]]\n| years = 1917\u20131948\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = Admiral Sir [[Martin Dunbar-Nasmith]]<sup>2</sup>\n}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = Lt-Col. G. H. Stobart, DSO<sup>3</sup>\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = Secretary,<br/>[[Imperial War Graves Commission]]\n| years = 1919\u20131948\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = Brigadier [[Frank Higginson]]<sup>2</sup>\n}}\n{{s-ref|{{Harvnb|Worsfold|1913|pp=84, 90}}, {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Vgd9L2EMlUQC&q=%22Director+of+Education%22+%22Transvaal%22+%22john+adamson%22+%221905%22&dq=%22Director+of+Education%22+%22Transvaal%22+%22john+adamson%22+%221905%22|title=General Report - Transvaal Education Department|last=Dept|first=Transvaal (South Africa) Education|date=1950|language=en|page=41}}|\"Sir Fabian Ware to retire\", ''The Times'' (London), 19 March 1948, p. 7.|\"The Imperial War Graves Commission\", ''The Times'' (London), 22 November 1917, p. 7; cf. minutes of the eleventh meeting of the Imperial War Graves Commission, 1 May 1919 (Commonwealth War Grave Commission Archives, CWGC/2/2/1/11), p. 1, and minutes of the twelfth meeting, 20 May 1919 (Commonwealth War Grave Commission Archive, CWGC/2/2/1/12) p. 7.}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ware, Fabian}}\n[[Category:1869 births]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:British Army generals of World War I]]\n[[Category:British newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the Crown (Belgium)]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth War Graves Commission]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Grand Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Croix de Guerre (France)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|British Army general and founder of the Commonwealth War Graves Commission}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Sir Fabian Ware\n| image         = Fabian Ware.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = Major General Fabian Ware in October 1916\n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=yes|1869|06|17}}\n| birth_place   = [[Clifton, Bristol]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1949|04|28|1869|06|17}}\n| death_place   = [[Barnwood, Gloucestershire]]\n| placeofburial = \n| allegiance    = United Kingdom\n| branch        = [[British Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1918\u20131948\n| rank          = [[Major-general (United Kingdom)|Major General]]\n| servicenumber = \n| unit          = \n| commands      = \n| battles       = [[First World War]]\n| awards        = [[Knight Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]]<br/>[[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]<br/>[[Companion of the Order of the Bath]]<br/>[[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]]<br/>[[Mentioned in Despatches]] (2)<br/>[[Legion of Honour|Grand Officer of the Legion of Honour]] (France)<br/>[[Croix de guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)|Croix de guerre]] (France)<br/>[[Order of the Crown (Belgium)|Commander of the Order of the Crown]] (Belgium)\n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = \n}}\n[[Major-general (United Kingdom)|Major General]] '''Sir Fabian Arthur Goulstone Ware''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KCVO|KBE|CB|CMG}} (17 June 1869 \u2013 28 April 1949) was the founder of the Imperial War Graves Commission (IWCG), now the [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]] (CWGC). Born in [[Clifton, Bristol]], he graduated from the [[University of Paris]] in 1894, and travelled to the [[Transvaal Colony]] where, as a member of [[Milner's Kindergarten]], he became Director of Education. Ware next became editor of the [[The Morning Post|''Morning Post'']], being fired in 1911 after several controversies.\n\nWhen the [[First World War]] started in August 1914, Ware attempted to join the [[British Army]] but was rejected because he was too old. With the assistance of [[Alfred Milner, 1st Viscount Milner|Lord Milner]], he obtained command of a mobile [[ambulance]] unit provided by the [[British Red Cross Society]]. In this role he began marking and recording the graves of those killed. Ware and his graves' registration organization were transferred to the [[British Army]] in 1915. This was to become the Imperial War Graves Commission. Ware ended the war as a major general, having been [[mentioned in despatches]] twice and continued to work with the commission. In [[World War II]], he was appointed director-general of Graves Registration and Enquiries. He fully retired in 1948, and died the following year.\n==Early life==\nWare was born in [[Clifton, Bristol]] on 17 June 1869,<ref name=\"Veterans Agency\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veterans-uk.info/remembrance/ware.html|title=Major General Sir Fabian Ware|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=[[Veterans Agency|Ministry of Defence Veterans Agency]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112162637/http://www.veterans-uk.info/remembrance/ware.html|archive-date=12 November 2014|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref> to Charles Ware, a chartered accountant, and his wife, Amy Carew, {{Nee}} Goulstone.<ref name= \"ODNB\">{{cite ODNB|title=Ware, Sir Fabian Arthur Goulstone|id=3674|ref=harv|date=2008|first=A. J. A.|last=Morris}}</ref> He was [[Tutor|privately tutored]] until his father died when he was 18. Ware then taught in private schools to pay for attending the [[University of London]]. When he saved enough money, he began attending the [[University of Paris]],{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=17}} graduating as a {{lang|fr|bachelier-es-sciences}}.<ref name=\"CWGC\"> {{Cite web|url=http://archive.cwgc.org/Record.aspx?src=CalmView.Persons&id=DS%2FUK%2F2|title=Sir Fabian Arthur Gouldstone Ware|last=|first=|date=|website=Commonwealth War Graves Commission archives|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181201223836/http://archive.cwgc.org/Record.aspx?src=CalmView.Persons&id=DS%2FUK%2F2|archive-date=1 December 2018|access-date=21 September 2018}}</ref> He then spent several years as an assistant schoolmaster at [[Bradford Grammar School]] and several other [[secondary school]]s. While working there, he was occasionally employed as an examiner for the [[Civil Service Commission (United Kingdom)|Civil Service Commission]].<ref name=\"ODNB\" />{{Sfn|The School World|1917|p=94}} On 1 August 1895, he married Anna Margaret,<ref name= \"ODNB\"/> with whom he would have a daughter and a son.{{sfn|Byrne|2014}}\n\nIn 1899 he started writing articles for the ''[[Morning Post]]''. He became the representative of the Education Committee of the Royal British Commission at the [[Exposition Universelle (1900)|Exposition Universelle]] of 1900 in [[Paris]]. After the exhibition, Ware worked as an inspector of schools for the [[Board of education|Board of Education]].{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=17}} He then became a member of a group of young Britons later known as [[Viscount Milner]]'s [[Milner's Kindergarten|kindergarten]]{{Sfn|Stamp|2010|p=72}} and in October 1901 was appointed assistant director of education in the [[Transvaal Colony|Transvaal]].{{Sfn|Worsfold|1913|p=79}} On 5 July 1902, [[Edmund Beale Sargant]], director of education for the Transvaal, wrote a letter to the [[Council of Education, Witwatersrand]], requesting their cooperation in selecting a committee regarding technical education. A committee was then formed, with Ware as the chairman. It recommended the establishment of a technical institute.{{Sfn|South African School of Mines and Technology|1910|pp=1\u20134}} In late 1902, the report on a technical institute  reached the [[Lieutenant Governor]] of the Transvaal who in January 1903 created a second \"Technical Education Commission\" again with Ware as a member. They again recommended a technical institute, and as a result the [[Transvaal Technical Institute]] was created with Ware as the chairman of the Institute's council.{{Sfn|South African School of Mines and Technology|1910|pp=1\u20134|p=}}{{Sfn|Page|1904|p=627}}\n\nIn early 1903 he became acting director of education when Sargant, in failing health, returned to England,<ref name= \"ODNB\"/>{{Sfn|Worsfold|1913|p=81}} and in July was made permanent director.{{Sfn|Worsfold|1913|p=84}}{{sfn|Malherbe|1925|p=305}} On 17 June 1903 he was made a member of the Transvaal Legislative Council.{{Sfn|The Edinburgh Gazette 23 June 1903}} Under Ware, the number of children in education in the Transvaal doubled in less than four years.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=21}} As director, he advocated a de-centralized system of education with responsibility largely in the hands of local authorities.{{sfn|Malherbe|1925|pp=305, 326}}\n\nIn 1905, he was offered the editorship of the ''Morning Post.'' He accepted, and moved back to England.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=22\u201326}} Ware aimed to make the paper \"the authority on all colonial questions.\"{{Sfn|Potter|2003|p=113}} When [[Lord Glenesk]] made him editor, the ''Morning Post'' had no offices, working instead in temporary wooden sheds.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=22\u201326}} He began expanding the paper by hiring [[Richard Jebb (journalist)|Richard Jebb]], who then hired many other correspondents. The two began focusing the paper on the British Dominions, a move they felt would increase circulation; they were proven wrong, though it did increase advertising revenue.{{Sfn|Potter|2003|p=|pp=113\u2013117}} Ware hired [[Robbie Ross]] as an art critic for the paper.{{Sfn|Fryer|2000|p=199}}\n\nAfter the [[First Moroccan Crisis]] in 1905, Ware campaigned heavily against war with Germany. He later said that {{quote|we threw the whole weight of the ''Morning Post'' against war with Germany. I am ashamed that I did not understand what we were doing at the time. I now believe that England ought to have fought Germany then{{em dash}}at any rate she is every month becoming less prepared, relatively to Germany to fight her than she was then.{{sfn|Wilson|1990|p=15}}|sign=|source=}}\n\nWare supported [[Social reform|social]] and [[tariff reform]] and he invited radicals such as [[William Beveridge]] and [[R. H. Tawney]] to contribute to the paper.<ref name=\"ODNB\" />{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=22\u201326}}\n\nWare was disliked by some members of the paper's staff,{{Sfn|Potter|2003|p=|pp=113\u2013117}} particularly [[Spenser Wilkinson]].<ref name= \"ODNB\"/> After coming into conflict with prominent members of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] over tariff reform, endorsing Richard Jebb (a move which cost the paper readership) and a failed fundraising campaign to buy the United Kingdom an [[airship]], he was forced out of the editorship and left the paper in 1911.<ref name= \"ODNB\"/>{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=22\u201326}} Ware then planned to form an independent weekly paper with funding from the countries of the [[British Empire]]; [[E. E. A. Duvernet]] proposed creating a \"United Empire Publishing Co.\" The project did not succeed.{{Sfn|Potter|2003|p=27}} After leaving the ''Morning Post,'' he became a consultant for [[Rio Tinto Limited]], negotiating with the [[France|French]] government.<ref name = \"Veterans Agency\"/><ref name= \"ODNB\"/>\n\n==First World War==\n\n=== Mobile ambulance unit ===\n[[File:Sir Fabian Ware 1869-1949 Founder of the Imperial War Graves Commission lived here 1911-1919.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Blue plaque marking Ware's residence at 14 Wyndham Place, Marylebone]]\nWhen the [[First world war|First World War]] started in August 1914, the [[Royal Automobile Club]] under its chairman [[Arthur Stanley (politician)|Arthur Stanley]] began assisting the war effort with the creation of the [[Royal Automobile Club Volunteer Force]].{{Sfn|Hall|2017|p=110}} On 12 September 1914, several members of the club volunteered their services to the [[British Red Cross]]. As a result, the Red Cross established the Motor Ambulance Department.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.redcross.org.uk/~/media/BritishRedCross/Documents/Who%20we%20are/History%20and%20archives/British%20Red%20Cross%20transport%20during%20the%20First%20World%20War.pdf |title = British Red Cross Transport during the First World War |last1 =  |first1 =  |last2 =  |first2 =  |date =  |website = British Red Cross |publisher = British Red Cross Society |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171104042234/http://www.redcross.org.uk/~/media/BritishRedCross/Documents/Who%20we%20are/History%20and%20archives/British%20Red%20Cross%20transport%20during%20the%20First%20World%20War.pdf |archive-date = 4 November 2017 |url-status = dead |access-date = 14 October 2016}}</ref> Ware, who had been rejected from serving in the [[British Army]] because he was too old, obtained command of a mobile [[ambulance]] unit with the assistance of Lord Milner.<ref name = \"Veterans Agency\"/> Though one of several such units in France, Ware's unit in [[Northern France]] was operated under a \"quasi-autonomous command\" with much independence being afforded by the joint finance committee of [[St John Ambulance]] and the Red Cross; he was given his own operating budget for three month periods.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=|pp=31\u201332}}\n\nAccording to the historian [[David Crane (historian)|David Crane]], the original object of the unit was to \"search for British wounded and missing in the district which had been overrun by the Germans during the retreat from [[Battle of Mons|Mons]], and to convey them back to the British lines or to a British base.\" However, by early October 1914, the unit had begun extensively working with the French, and by mid-October, it had added a mobile light hospital and medical staff. When the unit was disbanded in 1915, it had dealt with 12,000 casualties.<ref name=\"Veterans Agency\" />{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=33}}\n\n=== Graves Registration Commission ===\nWare was struck by the lack of an official mechanism for marking and recording the graves of those killed.<ref name = \"Veterans Agency\"/> In September 1914, following British defeats at [[Battle of Mons|Mons]] and [[Battle of Le Cateau|Le Cateau]], Ware's unit began sharing information with [[Robert Cecil, 1st Viscount Cecil of Chelwood|Robert Cecil]], the head of the Red Cross's Wounded and Missing department.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=38\u201342, 50}} In March 1915, with the support of [[Nevil Macready]],{{Sfn|Stamp|2010|p=72}} the British Army formally recognized a Grave Registration Commission (GRC). The commission represented a joint effort between the British Army and British Red Cross.{{Efn|Crane writes that \"in some ways the GRC remained a curious hybrid, semi-detached sort of unit - the Red Cross continued to supply men and vehicles, while Ware was given the local rank of major... and the army took on the costs of crosses, rations and fuel\" {{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=52}}|name=|group=}}{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=50\u201352}} On 22 May, he was made a temporary [[major]] in the British Army.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 21 May 1915}} On 9 September, the promotion was [[antedated]] to 22 February 1915.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 7 September 1915}} \n\nWare's work continued to expand: by May 1915, 4,300 graves had been registered. He was extensively involved in early organization of the commission, dividing it into two main parts and seven sections. That spring he began serving as an intermediary between the French and British governments over grave-related matters. The organization began handling requests at a headquarters in [[Lillers]], and the sections worked on grave maintenance. The organization was soon exempted from a ban on [[War photography|photography]] and a department of three photographers was created to photograph graves; by mid-August, six thousand graves had been photographed and eight hundred photographs sent to families. A further 18,173 graves had been registered. Around the same time Ware became unable to continue work with the Mobile Ambulance Unit, and began to solely focus on the commission. On 6 September Macready recommended transferring the organization completely to the Army; the transfer was completed by late October.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=|pp=50\u201352, 54\u201356, 59}}  \n\nIn his role in the commission, wares served as \"the sole [[intermediary]] between the British Army in the Field and the French Military and Civil Authorities in all matters relating to graves.\"{{Sfn|War Graves|1929|p=15}} Throughout 1915 and 1916, Ware led negotiations between France and Britain, resolving various issues, particularly that of [[land expropriation]]. Around June 1915, his efforts resulted in an 'expropriation bill' that began to be debated by the French government. Ware shepherded the bill through its passage, urging prominent figures such as the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|prime minister]], the [[Adjutant-General to the Forces|Adjutant-General]], the [[King of the United Kingdom|King]], and the editor of the ''Times'' to support it.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=|pp=59, 64}} The law passed the French government on 29 December 1917.{{Sfn|NYS Assembly|1918|p=548}} It gave Britain the ability to control their war graves in \"perpetuity of [[sepulture]]\"{{Sfn|Miles|2017|p=51}} and provided for the establishment of a British authority to manage the cemeteries.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=65}} \n\nWhen [[William Glynne Charles Gladstone]], a [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] and the grandson of former Prime Minister [[William Ewart Gladstone]], was [[killed in action]] near [[Laventie]] on 13 April 1915, his family attempted to have the body [[Exhumation|exhumed]] and returned to England. Despite a ban on exhumations established by [[Joseph Joffre]], his family received special permission to take the body and bury it in [[Hawarden|Hawarden, Wales]]. In response, Ware secured an order that banned all future exhumations.{{Sfn|Elborough|2017|p=55}}{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=|pp=68\u201376}} \n\nOn 10 September 1915 he was appointed a chevalier of the [[Legion of Honour]] by the Government of France.{{Sfn|The Edinburgh Gazette 10 September 1915}} By October 1915, the new Graves Registration Commission had registered over 31,000 graves, and 50,000 by May 1916.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwgc.org/content.asp?menuid=2&submenuid=11&id=11&menuname=Records&menu=sub|title=Records|publisher=Commonwealth War Graves Commission|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060807043150/http://www.cwgc.org/content.asp?menuid=2&submenuid=11&id=11&menuname=Records&menu=sub|archive-date=7 August 2006|access-date=17 September 2006}}</ref> On 11 February 1916 Ware was promoted to temporary [[lieutenant colonel]].{{Sfn|The London Gazette 28 March 1916}} After passage of the bill, [[Alfred Mond, 1st Baron Melchett]], the [[First Commissioner of Works]], and Ware competed for responsibility over the graveyards.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=81}} As the war continued, Ware and others became concerned about the fate of the graves in the post-war period. Following a suggestion by the British Army, the government created the National Committee for the Care of Soldiers' Graves in January 1916, with [[Edward VIII|Edward, Prince of Wales]] agreeing to serve as president.{{sfn|Summers|2007|pp=15\u201316}} It was set up with the intention of taking over the work of the Directorate of Graves Registration and Enquiries after the war. The government felt that it was more appropriate to entrust the work to a specially appointed body rather than to any existing government department.<ref name=\"IWC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/catalogue/externalrequest.asp?requestreference=WO32/9433|title=WO 32/9433 \u2013 Text of Memorandum put before the Imperial War Conference in April 1917|work=The Catalogue|publisher=[[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090307173755/http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/catalogue/externalrequest.asp?requestreference=WO32%2F9433|archive-date=7 March 2009|accessdate=15 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1916, the GRC was formally integrated into the Army as the Directorate of Graves Registration and Enquiries (DGRE).{{Sfn|Messenger|2015|p=244}} Representatives from various relevant government departments were included and in September 1916 representatives from [[Dominion|the Dominions]] were included.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=81}} Ware was made director of Graves Registration and Enquiries at the [[War Office]] on 15 May 1916, a post he held until the end of the war.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 20 February 1920}}{{Sfn|The London Gazette 7 July 1916}} While director, he was made a temporary [[Brigadier-general (United Kingdom)|brigadier-general]] on 12 August 1916.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 13 October 1916}} The DGRE heavily regulated graves, making every aspect from spacing of graves to marking the graves uniform.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=84}} Ware also worked to resolve disagreements between various ethnicity, decreeing for instance that: \"On no account should [Egyptian] [[Mohammedans]] be buried in Christian [[consecrated ground]]. . ., [[Jewish]] graves were to be marked with a double triangle on a stake,\" and \"under no circumstances should a cross be erected over an Indian Grave.\"{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=86}}\n\nWare further had to resolve conflicts between civil members and the Army. For example, [[Lionel Earle]], a member of the International War Graves Committee, objected to the Army's practice of marking the graves of [[deserters]] with unmarked wooden crosses. As a result the custom was abolished. In 1916, efforts to neaten the cemeteries began. Ware invited [[Arthur William Hill]], then assistant director of the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew]], to tour the cemeteries and advise upon further planting efforts in early 1915.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=|pp=88\u201389}} In the [[1917 New Year Honours]], Ware was awarded the [[Companion Order of St Michael and St George]].{{Sfn|The Edinburgh Gazette 26 January 1917}} \n\n=== Imperial War Graves Commission ===\n[[File:Canadian Corps - Canadian war graves.jpg|thumb|Canadian war graves near [[Ypres, Belgium]]. The crosses identify the graves as those of soldiers of the [[14th Battalion, CEF|14th Canadian Battalion]] who were killed over several days in May 1916.]]\nIncreasingly costly battles such as the [[Battle of the Somme|Somme]] and [[Third Ypres]] in 1916 and 1917 continued to put further strain on the DGRE.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=93}} By early 1917, several members of the committee believed a formal imperial organisation would be needed to care for the graves. With the help of the Prince of Wales, Ware submitted a memorandum to the [[Imperial War Conference]] in 1917 suggesting that an imperial organisation be constituted.<ref name=\"IWC\" />{{sfn|Summers|2007|p=16}} The suggestion was accepted and on 21 May 1917 the Imperial War Graves Commission was established by royal charter, with the Prince of Wales serving as president, [[Secretary of State for War]] [[Edward Stanley, 17th Earl of Derby|Lord Derby]] as chairman and Ware as vice-chairman.{{sfn|Peaslee|1974|p=300}}{{sfn|Summers|2007|p=16}} In September 1917, he was given authority to wear the insignia of a commander of the [[Ordre de la Couronne]].{{Sfn|The Edinburgh Gazette 28 September 1917}} In 1917 he was made a [[companion of the Order of St. Michael and St. George]].{{Sfn|Office of Commonwealth Relations|1919|p=485}} The Commission's undertakings began in earnest at the end of the war. Once land for cemeteries and memorials had been guaranteed, the enormous task of recording the details of the dead could begin. By 1918, some 587,000 graves had been identified and a further 559,000 casualties were registered as having no known grave.<ref> {{cite web |url = http://www.cwgc.org/about-us/history-of-cwgc.aspx |title = History of CWGC |publisher = Commonwealth War Graves Commission |access-date = 14 August 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130803025303/http://www.cwgc.org/about-us/history-of-cwgc.aspx |archive-date = 3 August 2013 |url-status = live |df = dmy-all }}</ref> On 7 October, Ware was made director-general with the temporary rank of [[Major-general (United Kingdom)|major-general]].{{Sfn|The London Gazette 1 November 1918}}\n\nIn June 1917, Ware proposed a 10 pound budget per grave, that became standard figuring for the commission.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=139}} In July 1917, a committee, consisting of the [[Director of the Tate]] [[Charles Aitken]], [[Edwin Lutyens]], and [[Herbert Baker]] toured the cemeteries in order to form a plan for post-war activities of the commission.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|p=103}} In 1917, [[Frederic G. Kenyon]] was made artistic director of the commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cwgc.org/learn/news-and-events/news/2017/12/07/08/55/sir-frederic-kenyon-sculpture-added-to-cwgc-collection|title=Sir Frederic Kenyon sculpture added to CWGC collection|last=|first=|date=|website=Commonwealth War Graves Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407012919/https://www.cwgc.org/learn/news-and-events/news/2017/12/07/08/55/sir-frederic-kenyon-sculpture-added-to-cwgc-collection|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> In 1918, Lutyens, Baker, and [[Reginald Blomfield]] were appointed the Commission's principal architects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/2KPN7n3yTJSyX9rQYkZDHHX/how-wwi-remembrance-monuments-created-beauty-from-chaos|title=How WWI remembrance monuments created beauty from chaos|last=|first=|date=|website=BBC|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407035523/https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/2KPN7n3yTJSyX9rQYkZDHHX/how-wwi-remembrance-monuments-created-beauty-from-chaos|archive-date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> The three architects often came in conflict over their views for the commission. Kenyon often served as a mediator.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=108\u2013117}} That year, Kenyon finished his report, titled ''War Graves: How the Cemeteries Abroad Will Be Designed,'' and presented it to the commission. The report outlined many factors of how the cemeteries would be designed, particularly emphasizing equal treatment of all soldiers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iwm.org.uk/history/their-name-liveth-for-evermore|title=Their name liveth for evermore|website=Imperial War Museums|language=en|access-date=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407012925/https://www.iwm.org.uk/history/their-name-liveth-for-evermore|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\nFor his work during the war, Ware was [[mentioned in despatches]] twice,<ref name = \"Veterans Agency\"/> once by [[Douglas Haig]] on 10 April 1919.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 8 April 1919}} In 1919 he was made a [[commander of the Order of the Bath]],{{Sfn|Sillar|1959|pp=926\u2013927}} and in 1920 a [[knight commander of the Order of the British Empire]].<ref name = \"Veterans Agency\"/>{{Sfn|The London Gazette 20 February 1920}} He received the [[Croix de Guerre]] and was made a [[Order of the Crown (Belgium)|commander of the Order of the Crown of Belgium]].{{sfn|Byrne|2014}} On 1 March 1921 he relinquished his commission and was granted the rank of honorary major-general.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 8 March 1921}} In May 1922, he was made [[knight commander Royal Victorian Order|knight commander of the Royal Victorian Order]].{{Sfn|The Edinburgh Gazette 23 May 1922}} Ware was given the authority to wear the insignia of a commander of the [[Legion of Honour]] on 27 December 1933 and the insignia of a grand master on 16 December 1938.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 5 January 1934}}{{Sfn|The London Gazette 16 December 1938}}\n\n== Post-war ==\n[[File:Memorial to Fabian Ware in Gloucester Cathedral.jpg|thumb|150px|Memorial to Fabian Ware in [[Gloucester Cathedral]]]]Upon the end of World War I, the commission could fully begin work. By April 1920, there had been 128,577 re-internment in France and Belgium and the commission was handling 788 cemeteries.{{Sfn|Parliamentary Debates|1920|p=254}}  Ware continued to work for the commission.<ref name= \"ODNB\"/> In March 1920, he predicted there would be over 500,000 graves and 1,300 cemeteries in France and Belgium.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=141\u2013142}} He oversaw the building of numerous cemeteries, with contributions from architects including Lutyens{{Sfn|Geurst|2010|p=184}} and  Blomfield<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cwgc.org/learn/horticulture-and-works/our-architects/sir-reginald-blomfield|title=Sir Reginald Blomfield|last=|first=|date=|website=Commonwealth War Graves Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622101005/https://www.cwgc.org/learn/horticulture-and-works/our-architects/sir-reginald-blomfield|archive-date=22 June 2019|access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> and the author [[Rudyard Kipling]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/features/what-was-the-imperial-war-graves-commission|title=What was the Imperial War Graves Commission?|last=Smyth|first=Hanna|date=|website=National Trust|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103130636/https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/features/what-was-the-imperial-war-graves-commission|archive-date=3 January 2020|access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref> The commission faced criticism over not allowing individual memorials for soldiers and repatriation of bodies of the dead, including in a petition that was presented to the Prince of Wales with over eight thousand signatures.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=145, 148\u2013149, 151\u2013154}}\n\nWare worked with [[William Burdett-Coutts]], a [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]], and [[Harry Gosling]], a labour leader, to write statements urging Parliament to allow the commission to continue its work.{{Sfn|Crane|2013|pp=145, 148\u2013149, 151\u2013154}} The efforts led to a debate in Parliament on 4 May 1920.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1920/may/04/imperial-war-graves-commission|title=Imperial War Graves Commission HC Deb 04 May 1920 vol 128 cc1929-72|date=4 May 1920|work=[[Hansard]]|publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625173055/http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1920/may/04/imperial-war-graves-commission|archive-date=25 June 2009|accessdate=15 December 2009}}</ref> Sir [[James Remnant]] started the debate, followed by speeches by [[William Burdett-Coutts]] in favour of the Commission's principles and [[Robert Cecil, 1st Viscount Cecil of Chelwood|Robert Cecil]] speaking for those desiring repatriation and opposing uniformity of grave markers. [[Winston Churchill]] closed the debate and asked that the issue not proceed to a vote. Remnant withdrew his motion, allowing the Commission to carry out its work assured of support for its principles.{{sfn|Longworth|2003|pp=51\u201355}}<ref name=\"A History p3\">{{cite web|url=http://issuu.com/wargravescommission/docs/history/1?e=4065448/5004091|title=A History of the Commonwealth War Graves Commission|publisher=Commonwealth War Graves Commission|page=3|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231002231/http://issuu.com/wargravescommission/docs/history/1?e=4065448%2F5004091|archive-date=31 December 2013|accessdate=28 December 2013}}</ref> Ware also fought for funding for the Commission. In the 1930s, he moved to [[Amberley, Gloucestershire]].{{sfn|Byrne|2014}} \n\nIn 1932, as a result of the [[British Empire Economic Conference|Imperial Economic Conference]], the Imperial Committee on Economic Consultation and Co-operation was established.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1933-11-22/26|title=Report of Imperial Committee on Economic Consultation and Co-operation. - Motion of Approval|last=|first=|date=22 November 1933|website=Houses of the Oireachtas|language=en-ie|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509030714/https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/dail/1933-11-22/26/|archive-date=9 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=24 July 2019}}</ref> Ware served as a British delegate to the committee, which published a report in 1933. In July 1932 Ware urged [[R. B. Bennett]] to support an 'Imperial Economic Committee' outside the [[British Treasury]]'s control. He was the first to seriously propose something of the kind, submitting a draft charter for the establishment of the 'Imperial Economic Commission', which would function as an economic [[general staff]] for the empire. The proposal gained little support.{{Sfn|Drummond|2013|pp=219\u2013220}} \n\nHe published an account of the work of the IWGC in 1937 titled ''The Immortal Heritage''.{{Sfn|Ware|1937|p=1}} He served as chairman of the [[National Education Union]], was an honorary associate at the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]],''<ref name=\"ODNB\" />'' and a director of the journal [[Nineteenth Century and After|''Nineteenth Century and After'']]. As a director of the journal, he made the decision to appoint [[Arnold Wilson]] as editor in 1936 and later insisted on his removal for poor coverage of the [[Spanish Civil War]] in 1938.{{Sfn|Love|2014|p=1036}} He was an adviser at the [[1937 Imperial Conference]].{{Sfn|Quigley|1981|p=159}} Ware also served the county of Gloucestershire in various capacities,''<ref name=\"ODNB\" />'' including as president of the Gloucestershire Rural Community Council from 1940 to 1948,{{sfn|National Archives|2019}} chairman of the executive committee of the [[Parents' National Educational Union]] in 1939,{{Sfn|Sillar|1959|pp=926\u2013927}}{{Sfn|Journal of Education|1939|p=14}} and Chairman of the Gloucestershire Branch of [[Council for the Preservation of Rural England]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/lords/1945/feb/14/war-memorials|title=War Memorials|last=|first=|date=14 February 1945|website=Parliament of the United Kingdom|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724164021/https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/lords/1945/feb/14/war-memorials|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live|access-date=24 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe outbreak of the [[Second World War]] saw Ware recalled from retirement to serve as director-general of Graves Registration and Enquiries at the War Office on 30 August 1939.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 6 October 1939}} On 3 September 1939 he was granted an emergency commission with the honorary rank of major-general.{{Sfn|The London Gazette 1 December 1939}} He also continued in his role as vice-chairman of the Commission.<ref name= \"ODNB\"/>{{Sfn|Miller|2017}} Ware ceased to be director-general in 1944 and resigned as vice-chairman of the Commission in 1948 due to failing health.<ref name= \"ODNB\"/>{{Sfn|New York Times|1949}} Ware died on 28 April 1949 in [[Barnwood House Hospital]], Gloucester. He was buried in Holy Trinity Churchyard, Amberley on 2 May. His grave has a CWGC-style headstone.<ref name= \"ODNB\"/> There are also memorial tablets to him in the Warrior's Chapel at [[Westminster Abbey]] and in [[Gloucester Cathedral]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.westminster-abbey.org/abbey-commemorations/commemorations/fabian-ware/|title=Fabian Ware|website=Westminster Abbey|access-date=2 December 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181202141455/https://www.westminster-abbey.org/abbey-commemorations/commemorations/fabian-ware/|archive-date=2 December 2018|url-status=live|ref={{harvid|Westminster Abbey|2018}}}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.cwgc.org/Record.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&id=CWGC/2/2/1/333|title=Records|last=|first=|date=|website=CWGC|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203055511/http://archive.cwgc.org/Record.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&id=CWGC%2F2%2F2%2F1%2F333|archive-date=3 December 2018|url-status=live|access-date=2 December 2018|ref={{harvid|CWGC Records|2018}}}} </ref> The road 'Boulevard Fabian Ware' in [[Bayeux]], the location of [[Bayeux War Cemetery]], is named in his honour.{{Sfn|Holmes|1992|p=368}}\n==Footnotes==\n;Notes\n{{notelist}}\n;Sources\n{{Reflist|4}}\n\n==References==\n\n=== Books ===\n\n* {{Cite book |title = Empires of the Dead: How One Man's Vision Led to the Creation of WWI's War Graves |last = Crane |first = David |publisher = William Collins |year = 2013 |isbn = 978-0-00-745665-9 |location = London |pages =  |ref = harv |authorlink = David Crane (historian) }}\n*{{Cite